{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":3440,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"f05b4430-fe3e-11e7-8e5d-e1b8077bf2ad","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/author/bryan/","params":{"slug":"bryan"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.70.20","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.70.20","host":"www.bryanmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{},"query":{}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"public, max-age=0","content-type":"text/html; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"4458-DIk/KhihKLDyc6rARtIiFG9/X5M\"","vary":"Accept-Encoding","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"59ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-21T00:06:33.263Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":3440,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"f0a397d0-fe3e-11e7-8e5d-e1b8077bf2ad","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/amp/","params":{},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.64.67","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.64.67","host":"bryanmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{"post":{"slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-2","status":"published","id":"5a45becefd55d33f00065ac4","uuid":"b3202bc1-7869-4d4a-acd0-3a716a452042","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 2","html":"<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 id=\"creatingtherdsinstance\">Creating the RDS Instance</h1>\n<p>Now that we got our web server, let's setup our db server.  First go to the RDS section of the AWS Console, then instances (on the left), then click that big blue &quot;Launch DB Instance&quot; button.</p>\n<p>We're going to select &quot;MariaDB Community Edition&quot; and on the next page we will select &quot;Dev/Test&quot; to remain in free and since we're learning.</p>\n<p>On the next page, check the box &quot;Only show options that are eligible for RDS Free Tier&quot; as that'll narrow down our select.  Once that's been checked, click the drop down next to DB Engine Version and select the latest version of MariaDB.   As seen below. in the settings section you will need to specify a DB instance identifier.  This identifier must be unique across all your RDS instances on your AWS account.  After we'll specify our DB user, I usually keep this root as we will specify a new user after for our WordPress site.  Make sure you save this password!.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.21.44-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.21.44-PM\"></p>\n<p>Next we'll specify our VPC environment for connectivity.  Make sure that it is on whatever VPC your EC2 instance is on.  We also do not want this DB publicly accessible.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.26.05-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.26.05-PM\"></p>\n<p>Now once that's setup, we're going to edit that security group we just created from the RDS setup wizard.  On the instance tab, click on your RDS instance and in the bottom pane, click the magnify glass icon from the left tab menu and then click on the security group as shown below:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.31.26-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.31.26-PM\"><br>\n<img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.30.17-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.30.17-PM\"></p>\n<p>We're going to go to the &quot;Inbound&quot; tab and hit edit, then add the following rule:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.32.37-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.32.37-PM\"></p>\n<p>The part highlighted is the GroupID for our WebDMZ security group.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>In a few minutes your RDS instance should finish intializing and you have successfully deployed your database service.  Next we will start logging into our Web instance that we setup in the first part.  From there we will configure our environment variables that we'll need in order to host a WordPress site.</p>\n</div>","feature_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Untitled-3-1.png","featured":false,"page":false,"locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 2","meta_description":"To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.  For this tutorial we will be using MariaDB.","created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","published_at":{},"published_by":"1","custom_excerpt":"To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.","codeinjection_head":"","codeinjection_foot":"","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"custom_template":null,"tags":{"0":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"1":{"id":"5a45c050fd55d33f00065ac5","name":"RDS","slug":"rds","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"2":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbab00","name":"aws","slug":"aws","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"3":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaaff","name":"tutorial","slug":"tutorial","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null}},"author":{"id":"1","name":"Bryan Monsalvatge","slug":"bryan","profile_image":"/content/images/2017/12/profilepic.jpg","cover_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Machine-Learning-in-the-Workplace_Blog-Banner-Image_1200x734px.png","bio":null,"website":null,"location":"Orlando","facebook":null,"twitter":"@BMonsalvatge","accessibility":"{\"nightShift\":true}","locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"tour":"[\"getting-started\",\"using-the-editor\",\"static-post\",\"featured-post\"]"},"primary_tag":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"url":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/","comment_id":"5a45becefd55d33f00065ac4"},"_locals":{"version":"1.19.0","safeVersion":"1.19","relativeUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/amp/","secure":true,"client":{"id":"ghost-frontend","secret":"45047af8aff6"},"context":{"0":"amp","1":"post"}}},"query":{}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"public, max-age=0","content-type":"text/html; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"6f8a-yCRmjSAHNGTF5lIVg4G2Unr7lUY\"","vary":"Accept-Encoding","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"67ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-21T00:06:33.751Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":3440,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"f1a158c0-fe3e-11e7-8e5d-e1b8077bf2ad","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-1/amp/","params":{},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.64.67","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.64.67","host":"bryanmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{"post":{"slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-1","status":"published","id":"5a45b548e32546392fdbaafd","uuid":"56039a8b-8a04-4f3e-b313-16348cad53b9","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 1","html":"<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress (4.8.2 at the time of writing) on AWS using EC2 and RDS (MariaDB).  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS with a new WordPress site.   In this tutorial we will not be diving into a multiple availability zone setup, however this will be a topic I dive into later.  All services spun up in this tutorial will exist within the AWS free tier!</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 id=\"creatingtheec2instance\">Creating the EC2 Instance</h1>\n<p>First log into your AWS console and go to the EC2 section.  Select the Amazon Linux AMI (2017.03.1) and for instance type select t2.micro instance (free-tier eligible).   Next let's go to &quot;Configure Instance Details&quot;.  We're not going to anything here, however it's a good idea to know what exact you're spinning up:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.55.13-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.55.13-PM\"></p>\n<p><strong>Network</strong> - Which VPC network our  EC2 instance will be connected to.  It is important that if you use a non-default VPC that this EC2 instance and our RDS instance are in the same VPC for private network connectivity.</p>\n<p>Everything can remain default here, we don't need to specify a subnet as we are not creating a multi-az setup.  Let's continue.</p>\n<h2 id=\"addstorage\">Add Storage</h2>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.59.44-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-6.59.44-PM\"></p>\n<p>We're going to keep this as default, we really won't need too much to start a WordPress site, and if we do we can use S3 for some of that later (will make a tutorial on integrated S3 later).</p>\n<p>Afterwards we will add our tags, however this is optional and more to keep your instances organized in the AWS Console.</p>\n<h2 id=\"securitywebdmz\">Security - WebDMZ</h2>\n<p>Here is where we are going to create our web server's security group.  Here we will want to allow inbound traffic over the following ports:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>22 -- SSH:  You have the option of scoping this down to your own IP, however if you do not have a static IP on your local connection you'll have to update this via the AWS Console every time you want to SSH.</li>\n<li>80 &amp; 433 -- HTTP / HTTPS:  This is to allow anyone to reach our web server.</li>\n<li>20-21 -- FTP:  We will need this in order to upload themes, plugins, and files to WordPress as it relies on an underlying FTP server.</li>\n<li>1024-1048 -- PASV Ports for FTP:  We'll specify this later in our &quot;vsftp&quot; configuration.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.05.09-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.05.09-PM\"></p>\n<h2 id=\"reviewandlaunch\">Review and Launch</h2>\n<p>Now we're going to review and launch our EC2 instance.  Once we go to launch, we will be presented with an option to create a &quot;Key Pair&quot;.  We will need this to SSH into our EC2 instance.  So give it some name and save it to your local computer.  I typically recommend placing it into your local computer's user folder under a folder called SSH (useful if you have lots of SSH Keys).</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.14.42-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.14.42-PM\"></p>\n<p><strong>Then launch!</strong></p>\n<hr>\n<p>Congrats you've spun up the thing that's going to be hosting our site files and serving web traffic.  Next we'll be creating the RDS instance, which is where we'll keep our WordPress database.</p>\n</div>","feature_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Untitled-3.png","featured":false,"page":false,"locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 1","meta_description":"Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress on AWS using EC2 and RDS.  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS!","created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","published_at":{},"published_by":"1","custom_excerpt":"Today I am going to go over setting up WordPress (4.8.2 at the time of writing) on AWS using EC2 and RDS (MariaDB).  This will be a pretty straightforward way of getting setup on AWS with a new WordPress site.   In this tutorial we will not be diving into a multiple availability zone setup.","codeinjection_head":"","codeinjection_foot":"","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"custom_template":null,"tags":{"0":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"1":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaaff","name":"tutorial","slug":"tutorial","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1